# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: prisma-orm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] In object-oriented programming, data-management tasks act on objects that combine scalar values into objects.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] For example, consider an address book entry that represents a single person along with zero or more phone numbers and zero or more addresses.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] This could be modeled in an object-oriented implementation by a "Person object" with an attribute/field to hold each data item that the entry comprises: the person's name, a list of phone numbers, and a list of addresses.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] The list of phone numbers would itself contain "PhoneNumber objects" and so on.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] Each such address-book entry is treated as a single object by the programming language (it can be referenced by a single variable containing a pointer to the object, for instance).
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] Various methods can be associated with the object, such as methods to return the preferred phone number, the home address, and so on.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] By contrast, relational databases, such as SQL, group scalars into tuples, which are then enumerated in tables.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] Tuples and objects have some general similarity, in that they are both ways to collect values into named fields such that the whole collection can be manipulated as a single compound entity.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] They have many differences, though, in particular: lifecycle management (row insertion and deletion, versus garbage collection or reference counting), references to other entities (object references, versus foreign key references), and inheritance (non-existent in relational databases).
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] As well, objects are managed on-heap and are under full control of a single process, while database tuples are shared and must incorporate locking, merging, and retry.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] Object–relational mapping provides automated support for mapping tuples to objects and back, while accounting for all of these differences.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] The heart of the problem involves translating the logical representation of the objects into an atomized form that is capable of being stored in the database while preserving the properties of the objects and their relationships so that they can be reloaded as objects when needed.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] If this storage and retrieval functionality is implemented, the objects are said to be persistent.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] Implementation-specific details of storage drivers are generally wrapped in an API in the programming language in use, exposing methods to interact with the storage medium in a way which is simpler and more in line with the paradigms of surrounding code.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] The following is a simple example, written in C# code, to execute a query written in SQL using a database engine.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] In contrast, the following makes use of an ORM-job API which makes it possible to write code that naturally makes use of the features of the language.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] The case above makes use of an object representing the storage repository and methods of that object.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] Other frameworks might provide code as static methods, as in the example below, and yet other methods may not implement an object-oriented system at all.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] Often the choice of paradigm is made for the best fit of the ORM into the surrounding language's design principles.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] Compared to traditional techniques of exchange between an object-oriented language and a relational database, ORM often reduces the amount of code that needs to be written.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] Disadvantages of ORM tools generally stem from the high level of abstraction obscuring what is actually happening in the implementation code.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] Another approach is to use an object-oriented database management system (OODBMS) or document-oriented databases such as native XML databases that provide more flexibility in data modeling.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] OODBMSs are databases designed specifically for working with object-oriented values.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] Using an OODBMS eliminates the need for converting data to and from its SQL form, as the data is stored in its original object representation and relationships are directly represented, rather than requiring join tables/operations.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] The equivalent of ORMs for document-oriented databases are called object-document mappers (ODMs).
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] Document-oriented databases also prevent the user from having to "shred" objects into table rows.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] Many of these systems also support the XQuery query language to retrieve datasets.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] Object-oriented databases tend to be used in complex, niche applications.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] One of the arguments against using an OODBMS is that it may not be able to execute ad-hoc, application-independent queries.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] For this reason, many programmers find themselves more at home with an object-SQL mapping system, even though most object-oriented databases are able to process SQL queries to a limited extent.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] Other OODBMS provide replication to SQL databases, as a means of addressing the need for ad-hoc queries, while preserving well-known query patterns.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] A variety of difficulties arise when considering how to match an object system to a relational database.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] These difficulties are referred to as the object–relational impedance mismatch.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] An alternative to implementing ORM is use of the native procedural languages provided with every major database.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] These can be called from the client using SQL statements.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] The Data Access Object (DAO) design pattern is used to abstract these statements and offer a lightweight object-oriented interface to the rest of the application.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] ORMs are limited to their predefined functionality, which may not cover all edge cases or database features.
[src:prisma-orm/object-relational-mapping] They usually mitigate this limitation by providing users with an interface to write raw queries, such as Django ORM.
[src:prisma-orm/prisma-schema-overview] The Prisma schema is the main method of configuration when using Prisma.
[src:prisma-orm/prisma-schema-overview] The Prisma Schema (or *schema* for short) is the main method of configuration for your Prisma ORM setup.
[src:prisma-orm/prisma-schema-overview] It is typically a single file called `schema.prisma` (or multiple files with `.prisma` file extension) that is stored in a defined but customizable location.
[src:prisma-orm/prisma-schema-overview] You can also organize your Prisma schema in multiple files if you prefer that.
[src:prisma-orm/prisma-schema-overview] See the Prisma schema API reference for detailed information about each section of the schema.
[src:prisma-orm/prisma-schema-overview] You can also use environment variables inside the schema to provide configuration options when a CLI command is invoked.
[src:prisma-orm/prisma-schema-overview] Prisma Schema files are written in Prisma Schema Language (PSL).
[src:prisma-orm/prisma-schema-overview] See the data sources, generators, data model definition and of course Prisma Schema API reference pages for details and examples.
[src:prisma-orm/prisma-schema-overview] Syntax highlighting for PSL is available via a VS Code extension (which also lets you auto-format the contents of your Prisma schema and indicates syntax errors with red squiggly lines).
[src:prisma-orm/prisma-schema-overview] Learn more about setting up Prisma ORM in your editor.
[src:prisma-orm/prisma-schema-overview] You can use environment variables to provide configuration options when a CLI command is invoked, or a Prisma Client query is run.
[src:prisma-orm/prisma-schema-overview] Hardcoding URLs directly in your schema is possible but is discouraged because it poses a security risk.
[src:prisma-orm/prisma-schema-overview] Using environment variables in the schema allows you to **keep secrets out of the schema** which in turn **improves the portability of the schema** by allowing you to use it in different environments.
[src:prisma-orm/prisma-schema-overview] See Environment variables for more information about how to use an `.env` file during development.
[src:prisma-orm/prisma-schema-overview] Prisma ORM supports formatting `.prisma` files automatically.
[src:prisma-orm/prisma-schema-overview] Data sources enable Prisma to connect to your database.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] In software engineering, a **schema migration** (also **database migration**, **database change management**) refers to the management of version-controlled, incremental and sometimes reversible changes to relational database schemas.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] A schema migration is performed on a database whenever it is necessary to update or revert that database's schema to some newer or older version.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Migrations are performed programmatically by using a *schema migration tool*.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] When invoked with a specified desired schema version, the tool automates the successive application or reversal of an appropriate sequence of schema changes until it is brought to the desired state.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Most schema migration tools aim to minimize the impact of schema changes on any existing data in the database.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Despite this, preservation of data in general is not guaranteed because schema changes such as the deletion of a database column can destroy data (i.e. all values stored under that column for all rows in that table are deleted).
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Instead, the tools help to preserve the meaning of the data or to reorganize existing data to meet new requirements.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Since meaning of the data often cannot be encoded, the configuration of the tools usually needs manual intervention.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Schema migration allows for fixing mistakes and adapting the data as requirements change.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] They are an essential part of software evolution, especially in agile environments (see below).
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Applying a schema migration to a production database is always a risk.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Development and test databases tend to be smaller and cleaner.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] The data in them is better understood, and if everything else fails, the amount of data is small enough for a human to process.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Production databases are usually huge, old and full of surprises.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] For these reasons, the migration process needs a high level of discipline, thorough testing and a sound backup strategy.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] In the steady state, one version of an application only understands one version of a schema.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] So the most basic strategy is to shut down the application, execute the schema migration, and then start the newer version of the application.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] While simple, this strategy causes a downtime.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Depending on the criticality of the system and its usage patterns, downtimes of various duration may be tolerated, but in some cases none may be tolerated at all.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] In those cases, one of the following zero-downtime strategies may be used.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Deploy a new version of the application which writes data in both the old and new formats (hence the name dual writing).
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] It's important to ensure consistency of these writes.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] After this point, all newly written data will exist in both old and new formats.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Execute a backfill in the database: copy data from the old format to the new format that existed previously, and hasn't been updated recently, so it's not dual written yet.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] After this point, the database has a complete replica of the data in both the old and new formats.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Deploy a new version of the application which switches to reading data in the new format, and stops dual writing.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] In distributed systems, it's important to switch the reading path before stopping dual writing, so this step may be divided into two.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Remove the old format data from the schema.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Deploy a new version of the application which tries to read both the old and new formats (hence the name dual reading), and works with whichever format is currently present.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Deploy another version of the application which stops writing the old format and starts writing the new format instead.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Everything should continue working normally as the dual reading will recognize that it has to read the new format for newly written rows.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Execute a backfill in the database: for all data that was written in the old format, move it over to the new format.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Deploy an application change once more that stops reading the old data.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] In this combined approach, the application is changed to both dual read and dual write.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Since both individual strategies ensure that the database can remain online without interruption, the combined approach achieves the same as well.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] This strategy allows for more fine grained control over the backfill, which can be divided into smaller batches, and feature flags may be used to toggle both the reading and writing paths more freely and separately from each other.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] This can also be useful when regular dual writing alone can't be guaranteed to happen in consistent transactions.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] When developing software applications backed by a database, developers typically develop the application source code in tandem with an evolving database schema.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] The code typically has rigid expectations of what columns, tables and constraints are present in the database schema whenever it needs to interact with one, so only the version of database schema against which the code was developed is considered fully compatible with that version of source code.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] In advanced applications, the migration itself can be subject to migration testing.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] With schema migration technology, data models no longer need to be fully designed up-front, and are more capable of being adapted with changing project requirements throughout the software development lifecycle.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Teams of software developers usually use version control systems to manage and collaborate on changes made to versions of source code.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Different developers can develop on divergent, relatively older or newer branches of the same source code to make changes and additions during development.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Supposing that the software under development interacts with a database, every version of the source code can be associated with at least one database schema with which it is compatible.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Under good software testing practice, schema migrations can be performed on test databases to ensure that their schema is compatible to the source code.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] To streamline this process, a schema migration tool is usually invoked as a part of an automated software build as a prerequisite of the automated testing phase.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Schema migration tools can be said to solve versioning problems for database schemas just as version control systems solve versioning problems for source code.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] In practice, many schema migration tools actually rely on a textual representation of schema changes (such as files containing SQL statements) such that the version history of schema changes can effectively be stored alongside program source code within VCS.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] This approach ensures that the information necessary to recover a compatible database schema for a particular code branch is recoverable from the source tree itself.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Another benefit of this approach is the handling of concurrent conflicting schema changes; developers may simply use their usual text-based conflict resolution tools to reconcile differences.
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Schema migration tooling could be seen as a facility to track the history of an evolving schema (i.e. schema evolution).
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Developers no longer need to remove the entire test database in order to create a new test database from scratch (e.g. using schema creation scripts from DDL generation tools).
[src:prisma-orm/schema-migration] Further, if generation of test data costs a lot of time, developers can avoid regenerating test data for small, non-destructive changes to the schema.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] TypeScript may be used to develop JavaScript applications for both client-side and server-side execution (as with React.js, Node.js, Deno or Bun).
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] Multiple options are available for transpiling.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] The default TypeScript Compiler can be used, or the Babel compiler can be invoked to convert TypeScript to JavaScript.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] TypeScript supports definition files that can contain type information of existing JavaScript libraries, much like C++ header files can describe the structure of existing object files.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] This enables other programs to use the values defined in the files as if they were statically typed TypeScript entities.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] There are third-party header files for popular libraries such as jQuery, MongoDB, and D3.js.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] TypeScript headers for the Node.js library modules are also available, allowing development of Node.js programs within TypeScript.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] The TypeScript compiler is written in TypeScript and compiled to JavaScript.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] It is licensed under the Apache License 2.0.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] Anders Hejlsberg, lead architect of C# and creator of Delphi and Turbo Pascal, has worked on developing TypeScript.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] TypeScript was released to the public in October 2012, with version 0.8, after two years of internal development at Microsoft.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] Soon after the initial public release, Miguel de Icaza praised the language, but criticized the lack of mature integrated development environment (IDE) support apart from Microsoft Visual Studio, which was unavailable then on Linux and macOS.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] As of April 2021 there is support in other IDEs and text editors, including Emacs, Vim, WebStorm, Atom and Microsoft's own Visual Studio Code.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] TypeScript 0.9, released in 2013, added support for generics.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] TypeScript 1.0 was released at Microsoft's Build developer conference in 2014.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] Visual Studio 2013 Update 2 provided built-in support for TypeScript.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] Further improvement were made in July 2014, when the development team announced a new TypeScript compiler, asserted to have a five-fold performance increase.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] Simultaneously, the source code, which was initially hosted on CodePlex, was moved to GitHub.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] On 22 September 2016, TypeScript 2.0 was released, introducing several features, including the ability for programmers to optionally enforce null safety.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] TypeScript 3.0 was released on 30 July 2018, bringing many language additions like tuples in rest parameters and spread expressions, rest parameters with tuple types, generic rest parameters and so on.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] TypeScript 4.0 was released on 20 August 2020.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] While 4.0 did not introduce any breaking changes, it added language features such as Custom JSX Factories and Variadic Tuple Types.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] TypeScript 5.0 was released on 16 March 2023 and included support for decorators.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] On March 11, 2025, Anders Hejlsberg announced on the TypeScript blog that the team is working on a Go port of the TypeScript compiler to be released as TypeScript version 7.0 later this year.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] It is expected to feature a 10x speedup.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] On December 2nd, 2025, Daniel Rosenwasser announced on the blog that TypeScript 6.0 will be the last release written in TypeScript itself, and TypeScript 7.0 will be the first Go-based release.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] TypeScript originated from the shortcomings of JavaScript for developing large-scale applications both at Microsoft and among their external customers.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] Challenges with dealing with complex JavaScript code led to demand for custom tooling to ease developing of components in the language.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] Developers sought a solution that would not break compatibility with the ECMAScript (ES) standard and its ecosystem, so a compiler was developed to transform a superset of JavaScript with type annotations and classes (TypeScript files) back into vanilla ECMAScript 5 code.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] TypeScript classes were based on the then-proposed ECMAScript 6 class specification to make writing prototypal inheritance less verbose and error-prone, and type annotations enabled IntelliSense and improved tooling.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] Syntactically, TypeScript is very similar to JScript .NET, another Microsoft implementation of the ECMA-262 language standard that added support for static typing and classical object-oriented language features such as classes, inheritance, interfaces, and namespaces.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] As TypeScript is simply a superset of JavaScript, existing JavaScript can be adapted to TypeScript and TypeScript program can seamlessly consume JavaScript.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] The compiler can target all ECMAScript versions 5 and above, transpiling modern features like classes and arrow functions to their older counterparts.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] With TypeScript, it is possible to use existing JavaScript code, incorporate popular JavaScript libraries, and call TypeScript-generated code from other JavaScript.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] Type declarations for these libraries are usually provided with the source code but can be declared or installed separately if needed.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] The TypeScript compiler, named `tsc`, is written in TypeScript.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] As a result, it can be compiled into regular JavaScript and can then be executed in any JavaScript engine (e.g. a browser).
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] The compiler package comes bundled with a script host that can execute the compiler.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] It is also available as a Node.js package that uses Node.js as a host.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] The compiler is currently being rewritten in Go for version 7.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] The compiler can *target* a given edition of ECMAScript (such as ECMAScript 5 for legacy browser compatibility), but by default compiles for the latest standards.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] Using plug-ins, TypeScript can be integrated with build automation tools, including Grunt (grunt-ts), Apache Maven (TypeScript Maven Plugin), Gulp (gulp-typescript) and Gradle (TypeScript Gradle Plugin).
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] TSLint scans TypeScript code for conformance to a set of standards and guidelines.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] ESLint, a standard JavaScript linter, also provided some support for TypeScript via community plugins.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] However, ESLint's inability to leverage TypeScript's language services precluded certain forms of semantic linting and program-wide analysis.
[src:prisma-orm/typescript] In early 2019, the TSLint team announced the linter's deprecation in favor of `typescript-eslint`, a joint effort of the TSLint, ESLint and TypeScript teams to consolidate linting under the ESLint umbrella for improved performance, community unity and developer accessibility.
